      text:
        'Mum diagnosed with COVID-19 while pregnant can\'t remember birth\n"I thought I\'d lost my pregnancy because I couldn\'t see my bump any more. I was really worried and disorientated."\nHer twins Sochika Palmer and Osinachi Pasal were cared for in the neonatal intensive care unit, where they remained for 116 days.\nSochika weighed just 770g at birth, while her brother Osinachi weighed 850g.\nTheir mother remained in her coma for more than two weeks after the caesarean.\nUke\'s husband Matthew told the BBC , "Every passing day I was hoping my wife was not among those who are dead." "We are a team, the idea she might not be there was really difficult to accept." (Twitter)\n"We are a team, the idea she might not be there was really difficult to accept."\nUke, who has two older children, told The Express and Sta r she was "very emotional" when meeting her twins for the first time.\n"I was happy that we were all alive, but obviously concerned about their severe prematurity which has its own risks," she said.\nWhen Uke regained consciousness she was suffering from "ICU delirium", which left her "so confused", she told the BBC.\n"When they showed me the pictures, they were so tiny, they didn\'t look like human beings, I couldn\'t believe they were mine," she said.\nSince being discharged from the hospital after nearly three months in the ICU, Uke said the twins are "getting better" each day.\nFor a daily dose of 9Honey, sign up here to receive our top stories straight to your inbox',
