      text:
        'Sex, Dating and the Sisterhood: Should you ever take back a cheater? Cazzie David and her dad Larry David in 2013. (Getty)\nAs a result, "being flaked on sucks", David declares, because she\'ll be left hungry and not "even get laid."\n"The only reason [women] will say no to a spontaneous hang is because it\'s after dinner and we don\'t feel hot," she asserts.\n"It will pain us to say no for this reason, but trust me, we will."\nDavid has attracted particular concern for drawing a correlation between heterosexual women having "no control" when rejecting men over the prospect of "being full", and one\'s sexual orientation or religion.\nIn a flurry of social media criticism, her opinions were called out for being "deeply unfunny".\nOne Twitter user claimed the piece read like it was "written like 12 years ago," asking, "Who still talks about men and sex like this?\nDavid\'s piece also didn\'t land well in the midst of trans visibility week, with critics slammed the author for her inability to write about sex in a progressive way.\n"I couldn\'t get past the second paragraph where she says \'both genders\'," one reader tweeted.\n"I actually think sex ed failed Cazzie David and it\'s NOT FUNNY," shared another.\nOthers took swipe at David\'s status as the "privileged" daughter of a celebrity, which she acknowledges in an excerpt of the essay. Cazzie David was previously linked to comedian Pete Davidson. (Instagram)\n"My problem isn\'t that Cazzie David wrote a book. It\'s that the spawn of celebrities always have a head start in entertainment, and as long as they ~acknowledge~ it, we\'re supposed to pretend like it\'s fine because they\'re somewhat talented," tweeted one critic.\n"I have read like six paragraphs of the Cazzie David essay and I cannot read another but man having rich well-connected parents seems like the most incredible drug in the world," said another.\nSome jumped to David\'s defence, one writing, "Going to go ahead and have an opinion about the Cazzie David essay, and the truth is, I liked it."\nAnother took one final, harsh swipe: "Imagine being the editor who picked the Cazzie David excerpt."\nFor a daily dose of 9Honey, sign up here to receive our top stories straight to your inbox',
