      text:
        'The girls were awarded the People\'s Choice Award for their heart-warming video. (Supplied) "The elderly often go unheard, and it\'s so important to make them feel loved."\nDuring the emotional video, residents open the girls\' packages and read their letters aloud, beaming and tearing up over the kind gesture.\nOne woman exclaims, "That\'s beautiful!" as she finishes reading one of the notes the students sent her.\nKairi says their project quickly became a testament to how "even doing little things," can "change the world slowly." "The elderly often go unheard, and it\'s so important to make them feel loved." (Supplied)\n"We really need to focus on the mental health of the elderly because they tend to feel more isolated and lonely," she tells 9Honey, adding, "and we learnt because of COVID, they were the most vulnerable, so we made letters and packages for them."\nDuring their visits to the St Vincents\' Care Services, Kangaroo Point Brisbane, the facility had microphones and couches set up with glass windows so they could safely connect with residents.\n"We also started writing letters to them to stay in contact since we couldn\'t see them as much," she explains.\nThe three teenagers admit they first "typed up" their letters on a computer to "check our spelling" but quickly fell in love with the old-fashioned style of communication. The girls quickly fell in love with the old-fashioned style of communication. (Supplied)\n"It was nice not to be on screens all the time," Summer laughs.\nSince the beginning of the pandemic, visits to aged care facilities have been extremely restricted to prevent exposure of the virus to vulnerable members of society.\nElderly people and individuals with pre-existing health conditions have been the most affected by the impacts of the virus.\nAfter making their video, the three girls agree it\'s vital to "all stay together and connect more than ever."\nTo celebrate their success in the competition, they simply "can\'t wait" to meet all the aged care residents they contacted during the pandemic. After making their video, the three girls agree it\'s vital to "all stay together and connect more than ever." (Supplied)\nVideos for Change is a national competition, created by educational program High Resolves, encouraging young people to make one-minute videos that raise awareness and inspire action.\nIn response to the pandemic, this year\'s competition challenged students to answer the question: "What does \'community\' mean in a crisis?"\nFounder Roya Baghai says, "These one-minute videos build empathy and touch your heart. They address universal issues and give us a sense of hope and connection at a time when it\'s never been more important."\nFor a daily dose of 9Honey, sign up here to receive our top stories straight to your inbox',
