      text:
        'RELATED: Women overwhelmingly represent unemployment figures during COVID Lisa Smith was rejected from a job she drove over 3,000km to secure. (LinkedIn)\nSmith notes she\'d even been "flaked on" three times by a prospective interviewer, or suffered the "eternal ghosting" of job officers never responding to her applications.\nThe woman concludes her post by noting she has "NEVER in all my years of recruiting or in my own job searches seen such horrible, rude, inconsiderate behaviour."\n"PLEASE read the resume first. Value applicants time too. Make time to speak to the candidate & be present," she begs.\nIn a final blow, Smith says, "Quit overlooking the unemployed. Learn what emotional intelligence is. Stop ghosting."\nAccording to the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS), Australia\'s unemployment rate peaked at 7.5 per cent in July during the pandemic. The unemployment rate continues to rise, but part-time work has jumped. (9News)\nWhile the numbers have dropped to 6.9 per cent as certain states slowly open up again, Kristin O\'Connell, a spokesperson for the Australian Unemployed Workers\' Union tells 9Honey, such action from employers, "really demoralises people."\n"It really breaks people to have constant rejection," O\'Connell notes, adding, "to be forced to not only apply for jobs when there are no jobs, but also to apply for jobs that they know they\'re not well suited to."\nExplaining there "simply aren\'t enough relevant jobs" in the current market, O\'Connell says the cycle of unemployment has been an issue long before COVID. "Now it\'s far beyond breaking point - we have double the number of people who are unemployed.\nO\'Connell says through her work, she\'s met people who have been forced into "cold calling businesses", or "walking around in their community, talking to places who aren\'t even advertising for employees."\n"People know that they\'re going to be rejected - it is a constant exposure to rejection," O\'Connell shares.\n"And that is just one of the many reasons why this is wasteful and harmful."\nWith over 2,000 comments on her LinkedIn post, Smith amplified the frustration many job seekers are feeling across the world.\n"I can definitely relate. When I was looking for a job in HR, I was blown away at how unprofessional some people were. They showed me how not to treat people," wrote one user.\n"I am on the job hunt as well and have literally had the job offered to me in person then never heard back from anyone at the company. That is just one of the many unacceptable behaviours I have come across. So inconsiderate of these recruiters," shared another.\nSmith added in the comments to her post, explaining she is yet to secure employment, and that "anyone who sees this and has treated a candidate in a rude or unprofessional way learns something from it."',
