        'To make matters worse, one fateful day Tracey discovered her wedding dress was missing from the room it was in, while her mother-in-law was staying with her. Tracey was mortified to discover her dress was being worn by her mother-in-law. (New Line Cinema)\nWhile preparing the spare room for her future relative to stay, in the 40 minutes it took to make the beds and accommodate Gina, she had snuck off with the gown to try it on.\nTracey explains, "I went to take a bathroom break and headed into the master bedroom...and what do I find but future [mother-in-law] struggling to yank my dress over her head."\n"I blurted out \'what the h*ll?!\' and she immediately started stammering \'Oh my God! OH MY GOD! OH GOD!\'" Tracey adds.\nTracey discovered her mother in law not only in the dress, but with a "bouquet of dried flowers" that had been on the bed before. Tracey quizzed her mother-in-law, only to be equally shocked by her rationale. (Getty Images/iStockphoto)\n"My future fiance is very disturbed by what happened," Tracey writes, speculating, "I think she was actually trying to pretend she was the bride...which for so many reasons, is so wrong."\nStartled by the exceptionally uncomfortable moment, Tracey quizzed her mother-in-law, only to be equally shocked by her rationale.\n"She responded that she was just trying to make sure the dress would fit me; because if the dress fit her, then it would absolutely fit me too," Tracey writes.\n"If it didn\'t fit her, then I obviously had some work to do. Never mind that I just had my final fitting and it had fit like a glove!" The train and zipper had been ripped on the gown. (Getty)\nAs if the moment couldn\'t get worse, Tracey claims her Gina "destroyed" the dress, breaking the zipper and leaving a brown footprint on the back.\nPart of the train was also ripped and Tracey\'s mother-in-law had decided to try the gown on without "wearing underwear".\nRather than offering to pay for the repairs needed to the dress, the mother-in-law proceeded to "lecture" her daughter-in-law for the exorbitant cost of the gown.\n"Clearly the trouble she had getting into the dress was a sign to get something less dramatic and ostentatious," Tracey writes.\nFor a daily dose of 9Honey, sign up here to receive our top stories straight to your inbox',
