      language: "english",
      text:
        "Professor Allen Cheng, Acting Chief Health Officer Issued to: Clinicians and the Victorian public Key messages\nA number of COVID-19 cases have been identified in the community in South Australia as part of the Parafield Cluster. Find out more on South Australian case numbers on the SA Dashboard . Anyone who has been in metropolitan Adelaide since Saturday 7 November 2020 should get tested, until they receive a negative result, regardless of symptoms. Anyone who have since Saturday 7 November 2020, but who have not been to metropolitan Adelaide can be tested with or without symptoms. They only need to isolate if they have symptoms. People who arrive in Victoria via plane with a high temperature or any COVID-19 symptoms will be asked to get tested when they arrive. People who have been to an exposure site requiring quarantine as identified by South Australia Health, are deemed to be close contacts and must be tested and isolate at home for 14 days from their exposure. They should also be instructed to contact the Victorian Department . People who refuse to get tested will be treated as a close contact and asked to quarantine for 14 days. Find out about the South Australian exposure sites , which are being updated regularly. People can find out more information about travelling from South Australia into Victoria . Doctors who are requesting COVID-19 testing are asked to ensure that a current contact phone number for the patient is included on all pathology request forms. Advise all patients who meet the testing criteria to they receive test results. What is the issue?\nThree is a community outbreak of COVID-19 in We are continuing Australia closely.\nCOVID-19 is a notifiable condition under the Public Health and Wellbeing Regulations 2019 and all confirmed cases must be notified to the department. All people meeting the testing criteria should be tested.\nPeople who have since Saturday 7 November 2020 should visit the South Australian exposure site web page to see if they may have been exposed. Who is at risk?\nPeople travelling into Victoria from South Australia are considered at risk if they have visited a high or medium risk setting anywhere in South Australia or metropolitan Adelaide any time since Saturday 7 November 2020. Anyone who falls in either category should be tested for COVID-19, and will be required to isolate.\nThe highest risk settings are updated regularly on the SA website.\nPeople of all ages have been diagnosed with COVID-19, but those most at risk of severe illness are elderly people and those with pre-existing medical conditions. Symptoms and transmission\nReported symptoms include fever or respiratory symptoms such as cough, sore throat and shortness of breath runny nose, anosmia or loss or change in smell or taste. Recent information on the transmission of the virus suggests that cases may be infectious up to 48 hours before the onset of symptoms, until at least 24 hours after symptoms resolve. The World Health Organization has confirmed that the main driver of transmission is from symptomatic patients through coughing and sneezing. Transmission by people without symptoms is also possible. Some evidence indicates transmission can occur through aerosol transmission. Who should be tested? Recommendations Advice for clinicians\nDetailed information for medical practitioners is available from For health services and professionals - page and the key guidance documents are the GP quick guide and checklist and more detailed Health Services and General Practitioner guide.\nIf you have a patient who has recently travelled to SA please manage as per the above guidance. Advice for patients\nIf you have travelled to SA since 7 November, please visit the SA website and follow the directions. More information\nHealth service and general practitioners on the Department website Consumer information\nSymptoms and risks on the Department website\nCoronavirus on the World Health Organisation website Contacts\nA public information hotline 1800 675 398.\nMedical practitioners needing clinical information can contact the Department Communicable Diseases Section on 1300 651 160 (24 hours). Subscribe now!\nKeep informed of emergencies affecting the health sector and critical public health issues impacting your work.\nSubscribe now to information including Chief Health Officer Alerts and emergency advice from the Department .",
