      language: "english",
      text:
        'Inside tips from one of The Block\'s judges.\nPrepare to go big this Christmas, says interior designer and The Block judge Darren Palmer. After all, we have a year\'s worth of celebrating with family and friends to catch up on. According to Palmer, there are four key decorating trends to look for this holiday season:\nLuxe\nThink a palette of pink, champagne and gold, complemented by a little sparkle. "This is a really sparkly, glamorous, elevated luxe look."\nGet the look with: Luxe at Myer Silver Prancing Reindeer with Jewelled Antlers Australian Christmas\nCelebrate all that\'s unique about Christmas at home with a moodboard inspired by the bush or the beach. Look for natural colours and textures and natives like gumnuts and eucalyptus.\nGet the look with: Australian House & Garden at Myer Faux Protea & Native Foliage Wreath Traditional heirloom\nEmbrace all the trimmings but keep it classic with a mix of red, green and white or silver. Get the look with: Heirloom at Myer Red Santa Countdown to Christmas Merry & Bright\n"If you want to go all out, now is the time. Put up the Santa, have all the flashing lights, and a big tree covered in every Christmas decoration you can find." Why not top off this more-is-more aesthetic with a neon sign or animated tree-topper?\nGet the look with: Mr Christmas Flying Santa Animated Tree Topper Mix and match\nThink of these trends as a guideline and cherry-pick the elements that work with your own style. Palmer likes to mix the "luxe" and "Australian Christmas" themes, adding in key elements from his own interiors range to get the look.\n"Take some elements from the Australian native theme, such as woven placemats or a grey or camel-coloured linen tablecloth – things that have a handmade feeling. Then add a little bit of gold and a little bit of brass. A woven rattan material plays really beautifully with brass, and those two things play beautifully against eucalyptus. They\'re a match made in heaven.\n"For example, I\'d use the candlestick holders from my range, they\'re brass and they have a ceramic earthenware base. They make a perfect table centerpiece. Then I\'d add big chunks of resin coral ." Layer the table as you would a room\nCreating a beautiful Christmas tablescape is all about using a mix of textures and heights, says Palmer. "You have to look at creating interest, in terms of where your eye falls and how your eye is led through something."\nStart with the base layer: a tablecloth, runner or placemats , or a combination of the three. Next, add in the cutlery, crockery and servingware. Then bring in some height with candlesticks or flowers. Finally, don\'t forget the details to really elevate your Christmas table.\n"You want to go all out and have napkin rings , bon-bons or crackers and beautiful candelabras," says Palmer. "Adding some Australian native foliage looks really gorgeous – whether it\'s in a napkin holder with your napkin, or it\'s part of a cascading arrangement across a table." Don\'t forget the outdoors\nFrom suburban backyards to inner-city patios, outdoor spaces will be an important entertaining area this year so be sure to give yours some attention by extending your decorating theme to undercover areas outside.\n"So much can be achieved with fairy lights or festoon lighting," Palmer notes. "Once the sun goes down, it will be appreciated that you went to that little bit of extra effort."\nAfter all the missed events this year, there\'s only one place to make up for it. Myer has endless gift ideas all in one place to make your celebrations bigger than Christmas. Style',
