      text:
        "Princess Diana's former butler and friend says the latest season of The Crown is 'accurate' Windsor Castle, where Queen Elizabeth II has lived during 2020, is Europe's longest-occupied palace. (Royal Collection Trust)\nLocated near Stamford, the magnificent property is no stranger to the screen, having appeared in Elizabeth: The Golden Age , The Da Vinci Code and Pride and Prejudice .\nIn previous seasons of The Crown , Belvoir Castle in Lincolnshire was the stand-in for Windsor Castle. Ardverikie House Ardverikie House, The Crown's version of Balmoral Castle. (Wikipedia)\nThe Crown 's cast may change every two seasons, but this Scottish baronial house has been a constant throughout the show's run.\nArdverikie House plays the role of Balmoral Castle, the sprawling Highlands estate where the royals spend their summer holidays every year. The royals spend their summers on the Balmoral Estate in Scotland. (iStock)\nThe property features prominently this season, with Margaret Thatcher and Princess Diana both subjected to the royals' famous 'Balmoral test' in an early episode.\nThe 19th-century residence may be familiar to fans of historical time-travel series Outlander . Wilton House\nThis stunning centuries-old manor has landed a plum role in The Crown , providing some of the interior shots for Buckingham Palace.\nThe palace's exterior is portrayed by London's Old Royal Naval College and Moor Park Mansion. Buckingham Palace is the Queen's main residence. (iStock)\nBuilt on the site of a 9th-century nunnery in Wiltshire, Wilton House and its 21-acre grounds is now home to the Earl and Countess of Pembroke.\nThe stately home has appeared in period films including Emma and Pride and Prejudice . Somerley House Somerley House appears in The Crown as Prince Charles' country home Highgrove. (Instagram/Somerley House)\nPrince Charles' beloved country home Highgrove House is portrayed for the first time by Somerley House, a Grade II listed Stately Home in Hampshire.\nThe beautiful property was designed in the 18th century and is not open to the public, though it is available as a wedding venue. Prince Charles' Highgrove Estate. (Getty) Wrotham Park\nThis Hertfordshire country home is the stand-in for Gloucester Park, where Princess Anne and her family live in Gloucestershire.\nIt was originally part of an estate dating back to the 1300s. Princess Anne's country estate, Gatcombe Park (Getty) Somerleyton Hall\nEach Christmas, the royals make a pilgrimage to Sandringham House, where they typically spend the festive season together.\nIn The Crown , the famous Norfolk estate is represented by Somerleyton Hall in East Anglia.\nIt mightn't be a British royal family property, but the Jacobean manor is incredible in its own right. The real Sandringham House, where the royals usually spend Christmas. (iStock)\nSomerleyton Hall's 12-acre grounds boast a walled garden, manicured gardens and a maze, and there's a ballroom to be found inside.\nYep, we'd happily live in any one of these properties, thanks... These are the most expensive royal estates, palaces and castles",
