      language: "english",
      text:
        '9Telethon: Palliative paediatric nurse talks about her \'resilient and amazing\' patients\nDuring her sporting career Camplin suffered a range of injuries, including a broken collarbone, dislocated shoulder, broken hand, broken ribs, a ripped Achilles tendon, dislocated sternum, fractured ankles, torn knee ligaments and nine concussions — plenty of opportunities to build and practice resilience. Camplin competing during the 2006 Winter Olympics. (Corbis via Getty Images)\nThat resilience remains her secret weapon, and she has made it her business to teach others how to improve theirs.\nShe\'s created The Alisa Camplin-AIA Vitality Workplace Resilience Toolkit , which has evolved to include the unique challenges workers have face since the beginning of the coronavirus pandemic in early 2020.\n"It\'s important for leaders in workplaces and families to practice good habits visibly, not just in their heads, so their colleagues see them," the athlete says.\n"You want to take them along on the journey with you." \'When I lost my son, it was one of the worst things in my life.\'\nCamplin and her family have been based in Hong Kong for the past two years for husband Oliver Warner\'s work.\n"We came here for a bit of an adventure," she says.\n"We followed my husband\'s work and thought it would be great for the family and it\'s been fabulous for us."\nTheir children Florence, six, and Felix, three, both adjusted well to the move.\n"It\'s been pretty good," Camplin says. Camplin homeschooling her children Florence, six, and Felix, three. (Instagram)\n"Kids are adaptable. They just need to feel safe and once they found friends it\'s been fabulous for them."\nThe coronavirus pandemic saw Camplin, along with parents around the world, homeschooling her children for majority of this year.\n"I\'m a working mother with my own business and I had to do a lot of prioritising through the year," she says.\n"There was a lot of pressure on me and my business, but on us as a family as well. I had to redefine success for myself and my business and really scale things to support those priorities."\nAnother major change resulting from the pandemic was Camplin\'s shift from speaking at in-person events about resilience to doing the same virtually.\n"I\'ve set up a home studio and I\'ve loved being a virtual speaker. It\'s pretty cool."\nCamplin also "doubled down" on her physical health, doing her best to "eat well, move well and think well" — something many struggled with during lockdown.\n"Having been a high performing elite sportswoman, I know what to do to get it right," she says.\n"If you are taking on too much it can become self-sabotaging." \'I\'ve set up a home studio and I\'ve loved being a virtual speaker.\' (Instagram)\nCamplin says she\'s also managed to practice flexibility, something she says is "applicable to everything", particularly for working parents.\n"There have been plenty of working parents this year put under pressure with their children," she says.\n"For me, one of the resilience factors I teach to help with this is to try and help people develop emotional awareness and emotional regulation. For anyone in any situation where they feel rising emotions and tension you need to be able to stop in the moment and go, okay, what can I control right now and what do I need to let go of."\nIf ever there was a year during which we had to accept the things we cannot control, it has been 2020.\n"The same goes for a situation at work where there is perhaps conflict," Camplin says. "You can\'t control all things, but you can control how you respond to them."\nShare your story by emailing Jo Abi at jabi@nine.com.au.',
