      text:
        'The ‘ICU Grandpa’ who cuddles babies will melt your heart\nThe hospital celebrated Deutchman\'s work by arranging a drive-by parade outside his home, accompanied by an NICU transport truck and helicopter.\n"In 2017, the story of our \'ICU Grandpa\' touched people all over the world," the facility shared in a tweet:\nSharing more details in a Facebook post, the Atlanta health facility explained 30 cars had taken part in the parade. Some carried employees and others patients "who had been soothed by David many years ago", all honking, waving and sharing their well wishes to Deutchman\'s family as they stood in their driveway.\n"For a grand finale, a Children\'s transport helicopter circled over his home, an emotional tribute to a man who has dedicated his retirement years to watching over our kids," the Facebook post read.\nParents shared their praise for Deutchman, one writing: "He has visited with [my son] Elijah many times over the past six years and would even stop by on our various ICU admits since."\n"He was always so thoughtful to our family. Thank you so much for being our rock through the most difficult challenge in our lives," shared another.\nDeutchman\'s story became a global headline in 2017 when a photo of him cradling a tiny patient circulated the internet.\nHe shared his love of his volunteer role, which he took up following a life-long career in International business marketing.\n"There are a lot of benefits to that warm connection of being held — when a baby puts their face against your heartbeat, there\'s a benefit there," Deutchman told PEOPLE at the time.\n"I came to love it, but not just because of the connection with the babies, but the whole atmosphere of the hospital."\nOn Tuesdays, Deutchman would cuddle babies whose parents were unable to be with them, and volunteered in the NICU on Thursdays each week.\nDeutchman would also provide support to the mothers of newborns by holding and caring for their children while they ate breakfast.\nHe is reportedly survived by Ronnie, his wife of 58 years, daughters Susan Lilly and Jill Deutchman, and his grandchildren and great-grandchildren.\nFor a daily dose of 9Honey, sign up here to receive our top stories straight to your inbox',
