      text:
        "A young Prince Charles once caused mischief on the Queen's Coronation Day The St Edward's Crown, worn by British monarchs during their coronation. It was last seen on Queen Elizabeth in 1953. (Royal Collection Trust)\nAlthough he may not choose to be known as King Charles III, instead the new king might prefer to use one of his other given names, such as Philip or Arthur or George.\nBut one thing is for certain: Charles will wear the St Edward's Crown during his coronation.\nIt was made for Charles II in 1661, as a replacement for the medieval crown which had been melted down in 1649 by the Parliamentarians, according to the Royal Collection Trust.\nThe original was thought to date back to the 11th Century royal saint, Edward the Confessor – the last Anglo-Saxon king of England. The coronation of Queen Elizabeth II at Westminster Abbey on June 2, 1953. (Syndication International)\nThe crown was commissioned from the Royal Goldsmith, Robert Vyner, in 1661.\nAlthough it is not an exact replica of the medieval design, it follows the original in having four crosses-pattée and four fleurs-de-lis, and two arches.\nIt is made of a solid gold frame set with semi-precious stones, including rubies, amethysts, sapphires, garnet, topazes and tourmalines.\nBetween 1661 to the early 20 th Century, the crown was adorned with hired gems which were returned to jewellers after the coronation.\nBut in 1911, the crown was permanently set with semi-precious stones for the coronation of George V.\nThe crown has a velvet cap with an ermine band.\nSt Edward's Crown is part of the Crown Jewels and is kept at the Tower of London. The magnificent tiaras worn by Queen Elizabeth II",
